          "&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cricket&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;ul&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;The &amp;quot;Timed Out&amp;quot; rule in cricket is outlined in the &lt;strong&gt;Marylebone Cricket Club (MCC) Laws of Cricket&lt;/strong&gt;, under Law 40.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;This rule states that a new batter must be ready to face the next delivery or at the crease within &lt;strong&gt;three minutes&lt;/strong&gt; of the previous batter&amp;#39;s dismissal.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;If the incoming batter fails to arrive within the stipulated time, the fielding team can appeal to the umpire to declare the batter as &amp;quot;Timed Out.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;The &amp;quot;Timed Out&amp;quot; rule is a rare mode of dismissal and emphasizes maintaining the pace and flow of the game.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;This rule applies to all formats of cricket, including &lt;strong&gt;Test matches, One-Day Internationals (ODIs), and Twenty20 (T20) matches&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;\n&lt;/ul&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;ul&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rare Dismissal Modes in Cricket:&lt;/strong&gt;\n\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;Other rare modes of dismissal in cricket include &lt;strong&gt;Hit Wicket&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;Obstructing the Field&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;Handling the Ball&lt;/strong&gt; (now included under Obstructing the Field), and &lt;strong&gt;Retired Out&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;These dismissals occur infrequently in professional matches compared to common methods like bowled, caught, or LBW.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Historical Instances of Timed Out:&lt;/strong&gt;\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;The first recorded instance of a &amp;quot;Timed Out&amp;quot; dismissal in first-class cricket occurred in 1987 when Andrew Jordaan was dismissed in South Africa&amp;#39;s domestic competition.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;There have been very few instances of this dismissal in professional cricket, making it one of the rarest ways to lose a wicket.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Purpose of the Rule:&lt;/strong&gt;\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;The rule ensures that the game maintains its rhythm and prevents unnecessary delays caused by players taking excessive time to get ready.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;It also serves to uphold the spirit of the game by emphasizing punctuality and readiness among players.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Recent Updates to MCC Laws:&lt;/strong&gt;\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;The MCC regularly updates the Laws of Cricket to address evolving scenarios and ensure fairness in the game.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;The 2022 Code of Laws included revisions to clarify several rules, including &amp;quot;Timed Out,&amp;quot; to ensure better understanding and implementation.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\n&lt;/ul&gt;\n",
