        value:
          "&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Siltation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;ul&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Siltation&lt;/strong&gt; refers to the process by which fine particles like silt and sediment accumulate in water bodies, leading to pollution and degradation of aquatic ecosystems.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;This type of pollution occurs due to activities like &lt;strong&gt;deforestation, mining, and construction&lt;/strong&gt; that increase erosion and sediment runoff.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;Siltation can disrupt aquatic habitats by &lt;strong&gt;blocking sunlight penetration&lt;/strong&gt;, reducing oxygen levels, and smothering organisms living on the seabed or riverbed.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;It also affects water quality and can &lt;strong&gt;reduce the capacity of reservoirs, lakes, and rivers&lt;/strong&gt;, impacting human activities such as irrigation and hydroelectric power generation.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;Preventive measures include &lt;strong&gt;soil conservation practices&lt;/strong&gt;, afforestation, and the use of sediment control techniques to reduce erosion.&lt;/li&gt;\n&lt;/ul&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;ul&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Suspended solids:&lt;/strong&gt;\n\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;They are small solid particles that remain in water due to turbulence or slow settling rates.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;Sources include agricultural runoff, industrial discharge, and urban stormwater.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;Excessive suspended solids can lead to turbidity, reducing light penetration and affecting aquatic photosynthesis.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Impact of siltation:&lt;/strong&gt;\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;Damages aquatic ecosystems by burying habitats and reducing biodiversity.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;Causes economic losses by reducing the efficiency of water infrastructure such as reservoirs and dams.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;Can lead to increased flooding due to reduced channel capacity.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Soil erosion:&lt;/strong&gt;\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;A major contributor to siltation, caused by deforestation, overgrazing, and improper land management.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;Erosion control measures include terracing, planting vegetation, and using sediment barriers.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Other types of water pollution:&lt;/strong&gt;\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Thermal pollution:&lt;/strong&gt; Caused by the discharge of heated water, impacting aquatic life.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Microbiological pollution:&lt;/strong&gt; Involves harmful pathogens entering water, affecting human and animal health.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Nutrient pollution:&lt;/strong&gt; Excess nitrogen and phosphorus lead to eutrophication, depleting oxygen levels in water bodies.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\n&lt;/ul&gt;\n",
