        value:
          "&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Law of Refraction&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;ul&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;Willebrord Snell, a Dutch mathematician and astronomer, formulated the &lt;strong&gt;Law of Refraction&lt;/strong&gt;, commonly known as Snell&amp;#39;s Law, in 1621.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Snell&amp;#39;s Law&lt;/strong&gt; mathematically describes how light bends when it passes from one medium to another with different refractive indices.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;The law is expressed as &lt;strong&gt;n₁sin&amp;theta;₁ = n₂sin&amp;theta;₂&lt;/strong&gt;, where n₁ and n₂ are the refractive indices of the two media, and &amp;theta;₁ and &amp;theta;₂ are the angles of incidence and refraction respectively.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;This discovery is fundamental to the field of optics and is widely used in designing lenses, optical instruments, and understanding light behavior.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;The law also underpins modern technologies such as fiber optics, laser systems, and imaging devices.&lt;/li&gt;\n&lt;/ul&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;ul&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Refraction:&lt;/strong&gt;\n\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;Refraction is the bending of light as it passes from one transparent medium to another due to a change in its speed.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;It is governed by the refractive index, which is a measure of how much light slows down in a medium compared to a vacuum.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;Applications include magnifying glasses, cameras, telescopes, and corrective lenses.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Refractive Index:&lt;/strong&gt;\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;The refractive index is a dimensionless number indicating the ratio of the speed of light in a vacuum to its speed in a given medium.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;It determines how much light will bend when transitioning between materials.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;Common values: Air (&amp;asymp;1), Water (&amp;asymp;1.33), Glass (&amp;asymp;1.5).&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Critical Angle and Total Internal Reflection:&lt;/strong&gt;\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;The critical angle is the angle of incidence above which light is entirely reflected within a medium, rather than refracted.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;Total internal reflection is a phenomenon used in fiber optics and diamond brilliance.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications of Snell&amp;#39;s Law:&lt;/strong&gt;\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;Fiber optic communication systems rely on controlled refraction and total internal reflection.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;It is essential in lens design for cameras, microscopes, and telescopes.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;Understanding atmospheric refraction helps explain phenomena like mirages and the apparent bending of starlight.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\n&lt;/ul&gt;\n",
