          "&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Gorges&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;ul&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Gorges&lt;/strong&gt; are deep, narrow valleys with steep sides, typically formed by the erosional activity of a river in its upper course.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;These are created due to the river cutting vertically into the bedrock as it flows downhill with high energy, carving out steep walls over time.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;Gorges are most commonly formed in areas with resistant rock, where the river&amp;#39;s erosive power is greater than the resistance of the rock.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;The formation of a gorge is a characteristic feature of a river&amp;#39;s youthful stage, where it flows rapidly down steep gradients.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;Examples include the Kali Gandaki Gorge in Nepal and the Grand Canyon in the USA, both of which highlight the erosive power of rivers over millennia.&lt;/li&gt;\n&lt;/ul&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;ul&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Upper Course of a River:&lt;/strong&gt;\n\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;It is the first stage of a river&amp;rsquo;s journey, typically found in mountainous or hilly regions.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;Rivers in this stage have high velocity and energy, leading to vertical erosion and the formation of features like gorges, waterfalls, and rapids.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Other Features of a River&amp;#39;s Upper Course:&lt;/strong&gt;\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Waterfalls:&lt;/strong&gt; Sudden drops in a river&amp;#39;s course, often formed where hard rock overlays softer rock.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rapids:&lt;/strong&gt; Sections of turbulent, fast-flowing water caused by a steep gradient or obstacles in the riverbed.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Meanders and Floodplains:&lt;/strong&gt;\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;These are features of the river&amp;#39;s middle and lower courses where the flow is slower, and lateral erosion and deposition dominate.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;Unlike gorges, meanders and floodplains are absent in the upper course due to high energy and steep gradients.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Oxbow Lakes:&lt;/strong&gt;\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;These are U-shaped water bodies formed from abandoned meanders in the lower course of a river.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;Their formation occurs due to sediment deposition cutting off a meander loop from the main river channel.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\n&lt;/ul&gt;\n",
