          "&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;55 m&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;ul&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;The standard width of a hockey field for international matches is &lt;strong&gt;55 meters&lt;/strong&gt;, as per the regulations set by the International Hockey Federation (FIH).&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;The field is rectangular, with a length of &lt;strong&gt;91.4 meters&lt;/strong&gt; and a width of &lt;strong&gt;55 meters&lt;/strong&gt;, ensuring uniformity in competitive play.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;The field is divided into halves, each featuring a &lt;strong&gt;23-meter line&lt;/strong&gt; that helps demarcate key playing zones.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;The dimensions are strictly maintained to support fair gameplay and adherence to international standards.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;The goalposts are placed at the center of each width side, with standardized dimensions to align with the field size.&lt;/li&gt;\n&lt;/ul&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;ul&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Field Markings:&lt;/strong&gt;\n\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;The field includes distinct markings such as the &lt;strong&gt;23-meter line, penalty spot, and shooting circle&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;The shooting circle is a &lt;strong&gt;D-shaped area&lt;/strong&gt; around the goal, where attacking players can score.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Surface Type:&lt;/strong&gt;\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;International hockey matches are generally played on &lt;strong&gt;synthetic turf&lt;/strong&gt;, which ensures consistent ball movement and player traction.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;Natural grass was traditionally used but is now rare due to maintenance challenges and uneven play.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Goal Dimensions:&lt;/strong&gt;\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;The goal width is &lt;strong&gt;3.66 meters&lt;/strong&gt;, and the height is &lt;strong&gt;2.14 meters&lt;/strong&gt;, standardized for all international matches.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;The goalposts are equipped with nets to catch the ball securely after scoring.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Regulatory Body:&lt;/strong&gt;\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;International Hockey Federation (FIH)&lt;/strong&gt; is responsible for setting and enforcing field dimensions and other rules globally.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;FIH regulations ensure uniform standards across international tournaments.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\n&lt;/ul&gt;\n",
