          "&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Bombay Session&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;ul&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;The Quit India Resolution was passed during the &lt;strong&gt;Bombay Session of the Indian National Congress&lt;/strong&gt; held on &lt;strong&gt;8 August 1942&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;This session was presided over by &lt;strong&gt;Maulana Abul Kalam Azad&lt;/strong&gt;, who was the President of the Indian National Congress at the time.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;The resolution, also known as the &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;August Kranti&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;, marked the beginning of the Quit India Movement against British rule in India.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;The movement called for immediate independence of India and was characterized by the slogan &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Do or Die&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;, given by Mahatma Gandhi.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;The British government reacted swiftly by arresting top Congress leaders, including Mahatma Gandhi, Jawaharlal Nehru, and Sardar Patel, effectively crippling the movement&amp;#39;s leadership.&lt;/li&gt;\n&lt;/ul&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;ul&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Quit India Movement (1942):&lt;/strong&gt;\n\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;It was a mass protest demanding an end to British rule in India during World War II.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;The movement was non-violent in principle but saw instances of violent clashes with the British authorities.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;The British government described it as the most serious revolt since the 1857 uprising.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;Despite the suppression, it significantly strengthened Indian unity and paved the way for independence in 1947.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Key Leaders:&lt;/strong&gt;\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;Although Mahatma Gandhi was the central figure, other leaders like Jawaharlal Nehru, Sardar Patel, and Aruna Asaf Ali played vital roles.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;Aruna Asaf Ali became known as the &amp;quot;Heroine of the Quit India Movement&amp;quot; for hoisting the Congress flag at the Gowalia Tank Maidan in Bombay.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Significance of the Bombay Session:&lt;/strong&gt;\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;The session demonstrated the Indian National Congress&amp;#39;s unified demand for complete independence.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;It marked a shift from earlier demands for dominion status to a clear call for outright independence.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Impact on British Rule:&lt;/strong&gt;\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;The movement created immense pressure on the British, who had to divert resources during World War II to suppress the unrest in India.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;It showcased the Indian people&amp;#39;s determination for self-rule and contributed to the eventual withdrawal of British rule in 1947.&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\n&lt;/ul&gt;\n",
