          "&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Given:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;The shopkeeper uses a weight that weighs 21% less than the actual weight.&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;He sells the goods at the cost price (CP).&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Formula Used:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;Profit Percentage = (Profit / Cost Price) &amp;times; 100&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calculation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;Let the actual weight be 100 units.&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; Weight used by the shopkeeper = 100 - 21 = 79 units&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;Let the cost price (CP) of 1 unit of goods = ₹1.&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;Total cost price for 79 units = 79 &amp;times; 1 = ₹79&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;Selling Price (SP) of 79 units = Selling Price for 100 units (as he promises to sell at cost price).&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; SP = ₹100&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;Profit = SP - CP&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; Profit = 100 - 79 = ₹21&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;Profit Percentage = (Profit / CP) &amp;times; 100&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; Profit Percentage = (21 / 79) &amp;times; 100&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; Profit Percentage = 26 (46/79)%&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Therefore, the shopkeeper&amp;#39;s profit percentage is 26 (46/79)%.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n",
