          "&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 1&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n\n&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\n\n&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n\n&lt;ul&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The word &amp;quot;neither&amp;quot; is a singular pronoun and must be followed by a singular verb. Therefore, &amp;quot;has&amp;quot; should replace &amp;quot;have&amp;quot; in the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct construction is &amp;quot;neither has any papers,&amp;quot; ensuring subject-verb agreement.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;This rule ensures grammatical correctness and clarity in the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;\n&lt;/ul&gt;\n\n&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 1&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n\n&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\n\n&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;Each of the two farmers wants the certified seeds but neither has any papers.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n\n&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\n\n&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n\n&lt;ul&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 2: &amp;quot;But either has any papers&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This is incorrect as &amp;quot;either&amp;quot; refers to one of two and does not fit the context of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3: &amp;quot;Yet neither has many papers&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This is incorrect because &amp;quot;many&amp;quot; is used with countable nouns, but &amp;quot;papers&amp;quot; in this context is uncountable.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;\n\t&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 4: &amp;quot;Yet none has many papers&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This is incorrect as &amp;quot;none&amp;quot; does not fit the context of the sentence, which refers specifically to &amp;quot;neither&amp;quot; of the two farmers.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;\n&lt;/ul&gt;\n",
